<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2006-06-27b.142.1" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/lord/100469" speakername="Lord Oakeshott of Seagrove Bay" colon="" colnum="142"  url="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199697/ldhansrd/pdvn/lds06/text/60627w02.htm#60627w02_wqn1">
	<p pid="b.142.1/1">asked Her Majesty's Government:</p>
	<p pid="b.142.1/2" qnum="HL6298">In the absence of behavioural change, what would be the annual cost to the Exchequer of (a) abolishing lower rates of stamp duty on residential property transactions while retaining stamp duty at 4 per cent. on transactions over &pound;500,000; and (b) abolishing the 1 per cent. rate of stamp duty on residential property transactions while leaving other rates and thresholds unchanged.</p>
</ques>
<gidredirect oldgid="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2006-06-27b.142.2" newgid="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2006-06-27c.142.2" matchtype="changes"/>
<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2006-06-27b.142.2" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/lord/100802" speakername="Lord McKenzie of Luton" colon=":" colnum="142"  url="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199697/ldhansrd/pdvn/lds06/text/60627w02.htm#60627w02_spnew1">
	<p pid="b.142.2/1">If all lower rates of stamp duty on residential transactions were abolished and only the 4 per cent. rate for residential transactions over &pound;500,000 was retained, the cost for 2007-08 is estimated at &pound;4.3 billion. If the 1 per cent. rate of stamp duty for residential transactions between &pound;125,001 and &pound;250,000 was abolished, the cost for 2007-08 is estimated at &pound;1 billion.</p>
</reply>
